# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-quicksight
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Clients often use this in combination with autoscaling (a process that allows a client to use more computing in times of high application usage, and then scale down to reduce costs when there is less traffic).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] These cloud computing web services provide various services related to networking, compute, storage, middleware, IoT and other processing capacity, as well as software tools via AWS server farms.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] This frees clients from managing, scaling, and patching hardware and operating systems.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] One of the foundational services is Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), which allows users to have at their disposal a virtual cluster of computers, with extremely high availability, which can be interacted with over the internet via REST APIs, a CLI or the AWS console.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS services are delivered to customers via a network of AWS server farms located throughout the world.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Fees are based on a combination of usage (known as a "Pay-as-you-go" model), hardware, operating system, software, and networking features chosen by the subscriber requiring various degrees of availability, redundancy, security, and service options.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Subscribers can pay for a single virtual AWS computer, a dedicated physical computer, or clusters of either.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Amazon provides select portions of security for subscribers (e.g. physical security of the data centers) while other aspects of security are the responsibility of the subscriber (e.g. account management, vulnerability scanning, patching).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS operates from many global geographical regions, including nine in North America.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Amazon markets AWS to subscribers as a way of obtaining large-scale computing capacity more quickly and cheaply than building an actual physical server farm.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] All services are billed based on usage, but each service measures usage in varying ways.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] As of 2023 Q1, AWS has 31% market share for cloud infrastructure while the next two competitors Microsoft Azure and Google Cloud have 25%, and 11% respectively, according to Synergy Research Group.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] As of 2025 AWS comprises over 200 products and services including computing, storage, networking, database, analytics, application services, deployment, management, machine learning, mobile, developer tools, RobOps and tools for the Internet of Things.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The most popular include Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2), Amazon Simple Storage Service (Amazon S3), Amazon Connect, and AWS Lambda (a serverless function that can perform arbitrary code written in any language that can be configured to be triggered by hundreds of events, including HTTP calls).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Services expose functionality through APIs for clients to use in their applications.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] These APIs are accessed over HTTP, using the REST architectural style and SOAP protocol for older APIs and exclusively JSON for newer ones.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Clients can interact with these APIs in various ways, including from the AWS console (a website), by using SDKs written in various languages (such as Python, Java, and JavaScript), or by making direct REST calls.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The genesis of AWS came in the early 2000s.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] After building *Merchant.com*, Amazon's e-commerce-as-a-service platform that offers third-party retailers a way to build their own web-stores, Amazon pursued service-oriented architecture as a means to scale its engineering operations, led by then CTO Allan Vermeulen.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] He also called for increasing the percentage of the time engineers spent building the software rather than doing other tasks.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Amazon created "a shared IT platform" so its engineering organizations, which were spending 70% of their time on "undifferentiated heavy-lifting" such as IT and infrastructure problems, could focus on customer-facing innovation instead.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In July 2002 Amazon.com Web Services, managed by Colin Bryar, launched its first web services, opening up the Amazon.com platform to all developers.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Over one hundred applications were built on top of it by 2004.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] This unexpected developer interest took Amazon by surprise and convinced them that developers were "hungry for more".
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] By the summer of 2003, Andy Jassy had taken over Bryar's portfolio at Rick Dalzell's behest, after Vermeulen, who was Bezos' first pick, declined the offer.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Jassy subsequently mapped out the vision for an "Internet OS" made up of foundational infrastructure primitives that alleviated key impediments to shipping software applications faster.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] By fall 2003, databases, storage, and compute were identified as the first set of infrastructure pieces that Amazon should launch.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] According to Brewster Kahle, co-founder of Alexa Internet, which was acquired by Amazon in 1999, his start-up's compute infrastructure helped Amazon solve its big data problems and later informed the innovations that underpinned AWS.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Jassy assembled a founding team of 57 employees from a mix of engineering and business backgrounds to kick-start these initiatives, with a majority of the hires coming from outside the company.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] They included Jeff Lawson, the Twilio CEO; Adam Selipsky, the Tableau CEO; and Mikhail Seregine, a co-founder at Outschool.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Near the end of their paper, they mentioned the possibility of selling access to virtual servers as a service, proposing the company could generate revenue from the new infrastructure investment.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Thereafter Pinkham, Willem van Biljon, and lead developer Christopher Brown developed the Amazon EC2 service, with a team in Cape Town, South Africa.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In October 2004, Amazon released Alexa Web Information Service (AWIS) as beta.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In November 2004, AWS launched its first infrastructure service, as beta: Simple Queue Service (SQS)., and officially launched in July 2006.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] On March 14, 2006, AWS launched Amazon S3 cloud storage, and that was the first AWS' IaaS that was generally available, followed by EC2 in August 2006.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Pi Corporation, a startup Paul Maritz co-founded, was the first beta-user of EC2 outside of Amazon, while Microsoft was among EC2's first enterprise customers.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Later that year SmugMug, one of the early AWS adopters, attributed savings of around US$400,000 in storage costs to S3.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] According to Vogels, S3 was built with 8 microservices when it launched in 2006 and had over 300 microservices by 2022.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In September 2007, AWS announced its annual *Start-up Challenge*, a contest with prizes worth $100,000 for entrepreneurs and software developers in the US using AWS services such as S3 and EC2 to build their businesses.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The first edition saw participation from Justin.tv, which Amazon later acquired in 2014.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Ooyala, an online media company, was the eventual winner.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS offers, as of June 16, 2022, two block-storage options: the EC2 Instance Store and the Elastic Block Store (EBS).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Additional AWS services from this period include SimpleDB, Mechanical Turk, Elastic Beanstalk, Relational Database Service, DynamoDB, CloudWatch, Simple Workflow, CloudFront, and Availability Zones.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In November 2010, it was reported that all of Amazon.com's retail sites had migrated to AWS.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Prior to 2012, AWS was considered a part of Amazon.com and so its revenue was not delineated in Amazon financial statements.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In that year industry watchers for the first time estimated AWS revenue to be over $1.5 billion.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] On November 27, 2012, AWS hosted its first major annual conference, *re:Invent* with a focus on AWS's partners and ecosystem, with over 150 sessions.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The three-day event was held in Las Vegas because of its relatively cheaper connectivity with locations across the United States and the rest of the world.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Andy Jassy and Werner Vogels presented keynotes, with Jeff Bezos joining Vogels for a fireside chat.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS opened early registrations at US$1,099 per head for their customers from over 190 countries.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] On stage with Andy Jassy at the event which saw around 6000 attendees, Reed Hastings, CEO at Netflix, announced plans to migrate 100% of Netflix's infrastructure to AWS.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] To support industry-wide training and skills standardization, AWS began offering a certification program for computer engineers, on April 30, 2013, to highlight expertise in cloud computing.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Later that year, in October, AWS launched *Activate*, a program for start-ups worldwide to leverage AWS credits, third-party integrations, and free access to AWS experts to help build their business.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2014, AWS launched its partner network, AWS Partner Network (APN), which is focused on helping AWS-based companies grow and scale the success of their business with close collaboration and best practices.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In October 2014, Amazon Aurora was launched.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In January 2015, Amazon Web Services acquired Annapurna Labs, an Israel-based microelectronics company for a reported US$350–370M.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In April 2015, Amazon.com reported AWS was profitable, with sales of $1.57 billion in the first quarter of the year and $265 million of operating income.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Founder Jeff Bezos described it as a fast-growing $5 billion business; analysts described it as "surprisingly more profitable than forecast".
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In October, Amazon.com said in its Q3 earnings report that AWS's operating income was $521 million, with operating margins at 25 percent.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS's 2015 Q3 revenue was $2.1 billion, a 78% increase from 2014's Q3 revenue of $1.17 billion.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] 2015 Q4 revenue for the AWS segment increased 69.5% y/y to $2.4 billion with a 28.5% operating margin, giving AWS a $9.6 billion run rate.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2015, Gartner estimated that AWS customers are deploying 10x more infrastructure on AWS than the combined adoption of the next 14 providers.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2016 Q1, revenue was $2.57 billion with net income of $604 million, a 64% increase over 2015 Q1 that resulted in AWS being more profitable than Amazon's North American retail business for the first time.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Jassy was thereafter promoted to CEO of the division.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Around the same time, Amazon experienced a 42% rise in stock value as a result of increased earnings, of which AWS contributed 56% to corporate profits.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS had $17.46 billion in annual revenue in 2017.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] By the end of 2020, the number had grown to $46 billion.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Reflecting the success of AWS, Jassy's annual compensation in 2017 hit nearly $36 million.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In January 2018, Amazon launched a unified autoscaling service on AWS.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] This new service unifies and builds on AWS existing, service-specific, scaling features like EC2 Auto Scaling groups, that was launched in August 2006.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In November 2018, AWS announced customized ARM cores for use in its servers.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Also in November 2018, AWS created ground stations to communicate with customers' satellites.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2019, AWS reported 37% yearly growth and accounted for 12% of Amazon's revenue (up from 11% in 2018).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In April 2021, AWS reported 32% yearly growth and accounted for 32% of $41.8 billion cloud market in Q1 2021.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In January 2022, AWS joined the MACH Alliance, a non-profit enterprise technology advocacy group.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In June 2022, it was reported that in 2019 Capital One had not secured their AWS resources properly, and was subject to a data breach by a former AWS employee.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The employee was convicted of hacking into the company's cloud servers to steal customer data and use computer power to mine cryptocurrency.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The ex-employee was able to download the personal information of more than 100 million Capital One customers.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In June 2022, AWS announced they had launched the AWS Snowcone, a small computing device, to the International Space Station on the Axiom Mission 1.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In September 2023, AWS announced it would become AI startup Anthropic's primary cloud provider.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Amazon has committed to investing up to $4 billion in Anthropic and will have a minority ownership position in the company.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In April 2024, AWS announced a new service called Deadline Cloud, which lets customers set up, deploy and scale up graphics and visual effects rendering pipelines on AWS cloud infrastructure.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In July 2024, AWS won a $1.3 billion (A$2 billion) contract with Australia's government to build a top-secret cloud service.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The service included a partnership with the Australian Signals Directorate (ASD).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The ASD director general Rachel Noble said the service would "provide a state-of-the-art collaborative space for our intelligence and defense community to store and access top-secret data”.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In December 2024, AWS announced Amazon Nova, its own family of foundation models.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] These models, offered through Amazon Bedrock, are designed for various tasks including content generation, video understanding, and building agentic applications.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] They are available in six different sizes.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In March and April of 2026, during the 2026 Iran War, Iranian drone and missile strikes damaged AWS data centers in the United Arab Emirates (me-central-1) and Bahrain (me-south-1) regions, in the first deliberate military targeting of a commercial data center.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Iran claimed the data centers hosted US military workloads.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS advised customers to migrate to other regions.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In October 2013, AWS was awarded a $600M contract with the CIA.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] By 2019, it was reported that more than 80% of Germany's listed DAX companies used AWS.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Navy said it moved 72,000 users from six commands to an AWS cloud system as a first step toward pushing all of its data and analytics onto the cloud.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In January 2021, Amazon announced that it would suspend Parler from Amazon Web Services, stating Parler hosted “violent content” that violates its terms of service.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Later in 2021, DISH Network announced it would develop and launch its 5G network on AWS.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] It was also reported that spy agencies and government departments in the UK, such as GCHQ, MI5, MI6, and the Ministry of Defence, contracted AWS to host their classified materials.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2022, Amazon shared a $9 billion contract from the United States Department of Defense for cloud computing with Google, Microsoft, and Oracle.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS won a $581 million contract from the U.S.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Air Force in January 2026 to provide cloud services and specific Amazon data centers as part of the Cloud One Program, the Air Force's enterprise cloud environment.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Multiple financial services firms have shifted to AWS in some form.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Notable customers include NASA and the Obama presidential campaign of 2012.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] As of October 2025, AWS has distinct operations in 38 geographical "regions": nine in North America, two in South America, nine in Europe, four in the Middle East, one in Africa, thirteen in the Asia–Pacific, and three in Australia and New Zealand.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Most AWS regions are enabled by default for AWS accounts.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Regions introduced after 20 March 2019 are considered to be *opt-in* regions, requiring a user to explicitly enable them in order for the region to be usable in the account.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] For opt-in regions, Identity and Access Management (IAM) resources such as users and roles are only propagated to the regions that are enabled.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Each region is wholly contained within a single country and all of its data and services stay within the designated region.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Each region has multiple "Availability Zones", which consist of one or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Availability Zones do not automatically provide additional scalability or redundancy within a region, since they are intentionally isolated from each other to prevent outages from spreading between zones.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Several services can operate across Availability Zones (e.g., S3, DynamoDB) while others can be configured to replicate across zones to spread demand and avoid downtime from failures.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] As of December 2014, Amazon Web Services operated an estimated 1.4 million servers across 11 regions and 28 availability zones.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] As of March 2024, AWS had announced the planned launch of six additional regions in Malaysia, Mexico, New Zealand, Thailand, Saudi Arabia, and the European Union.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In mid March 2023, Amazon Web Services signed a cooperation agreement with the New Zealand Government to build large data centers in New Zealand.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS also has "pop-up lofts" in different locations around the world.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] These market AWS to entrepreneurs and startups in different tech industries in a physical location.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Visitors can work or relax inside the loft, or learn more about what they can do with AWS.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In June 2014, AWS opened their first temporary pop-up loft in San Francisco.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In May 2015 they expanded to New York City, and in September 2015 expanded to Berlin.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS opened its fourth location, in Tel Aviv from March 1, 2016, to March 22, 2016.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] A pop-up loft was open in London from September 10 to October 29, 2015.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The pop-up lofts in New York and San Francisco are indefinitely closed due to the COVID-19 pandemic while Tokyo has remained open in a limited capacity.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2017, AWS launched AWS re/Start in the United Kingdom to help young adults and military veterans retrain in technology-related skills.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In partnership with the Prince's Trust and the Ministry of Defence (MoD), AWS will help to provide re-training opportunities for young people from disadvantaged backgrounds and former military personnel.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS is working alongside a number of partner companies including Cloudreach, Sage Group, EDF Energy, and Tesco Bank.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In April 2022, AWS announced that the organization had committed more than $30 million over three years to early-stage start-ups led by Black, Latino, LGBTQIA+, and women founders as part of its AWS impact Accelerator.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The Initiative offers qualifying start-ups up to $225,000 in cash, credits, extensive training, mentoring, technical guidance and includes up to $100,000 in AWS service credits.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2014, AWS claimed its aim was to achieve 100% renewable energy usage in the future.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2016, Greenpeace assessed major tech companies—including cloud services providers like AWS, Microsoft, Oracle, Google, IBM, Salesforce and Rackspace—based on their level of "clean energy" usage.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Greenpeace evaluated companies on their mix of renewable-energy sources; transparency; renewable-energy commitment and policies; energy efficiency and greenhouse-gas mitigation; renewable-energy procurement; and advocacy.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The group gave AWS an overall "C" grade.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Greenpeace credited AWS for its advances toward greener computing in recent years and its plans to launch multiple wind and solar farms across the United States.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The organization stated that Amazon is opaque about its carbon footprint.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In January 2021, AWS joined an industry pledge to achieve climate neutrality of data centers by 2030, the Climate Neutral Data Centre Pact.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] As of 2023, Amazon as a whole is the largest corporate purchaser of renewable energy in the world, a position it has held since 2020, and has a global portfolio of over 20 GW of renewable energy capacity.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2022, 90% of all Amazon operations, including data centers, were powered by renewables.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2024, AWS paid $650 million for a data center at the 2.5 GW Susquehanna nuclear power plant, connected at 300 MW.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The power increase depends on Amazon's expansion of the data center.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] US Department of Homeland Security has employed the software ATLAS, which runs on Amazon Cloud.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] It scanned more than 16.5 million records of naturalized Americans and flagged approximately 124,000 of them for manual analysis and review by USCIS officers regarding denaturalization.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Some of the scanned data came from the Terrorist Screening Database and the National Crime Information Center.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The algorithm and the criteria for the algorithm were secret.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Amazon faced protests from its own employees and activists for the anti-migrant collaboration with authorities.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The contract for Project Nimbus drew rebuke and condemnation from the companies' shareholders as well as their employees, over concerns that the project would lead to abuses of Palestinians' human rights in the context of the ongoing occupation and the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Specifically, they voice concern over how the technology will enable further surveillance of Palestinians and unlawful data collection on them as well as facilitate the expansion of Israel's illegal settlements on Palestinian land.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] A government procurement document featuring 'obligatory customers' of Nimbus, including "two of Israel’s leading state-owned weapons manufacturers" Israel Aerospace Industries and Rafael Advanced Defense Systems, was published in 2021 with periodic updates since (up to Oct 2023).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS has been noted to work with Chinese companies under varying degrees of U.S. government sanctions, such as Hikvision and Dahua Technology, which have been accused to enabling mass surveillance and human rights abuses in China and elsewhere.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In July 2025, a security researcher disclosed a supply-chain vulnerability in the Amazon Q Developer Extension (version 1.84) for Visual Studio Code.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The issue involved a malicious pull request to the project's GitHub repository, which introduced a prompt instructing the AI assistant to delete local files and AWS resources.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS acknowledged the issue in Security Bulletin AWS‑2025‑015 and released version 1.85 to remove the injected prompt.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The company stated that no customer systems or data were affected.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] However, critics including Corey Quinn, writing in Last Week in AWS, questioned the transparency of the response, noting the absence of a changelog entry, a CVE assignment, or a public statement beyond the bulletin.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In response to the Log4Shell vulnerability, AWS released hot patch solutions to mitigate risks in Java applications across various environments, including standalone servers, Kubernetes clusters, and Elastic Container Service (ECS).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] These patches were designed for both AWS and non-AWS environments.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] However, researchers from Unit 42 at Palo Alto Networks identified critical security flaws in these patches that could be exploited for container escape and privilege escalation, potentially granting attackers unauthorized root-level access to the host system.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS addressed these vulnerabilities by releasing updated patches on April 19, 2022.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Users who deployed the initial patches were advised to upgrade to the latest versions to mitigate security risks.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In April 2024, security researchers from Miggo security identified a configuration vulnerability in AWS Application Load Balancer (ALB) that could allow attackers to bypass access controls and compromise web applications.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The issue stemmed from how some users configured ALB's authentication handoff to third-party services, potentially enabling unauthorized access to application data.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] On July 11, 2024, AWS confirmed the issue affecting its customers, and on July 19, 2024, AWS updated its documentation accordingly to recommend more secure implementation practices.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] In 2026, Amazon Web Services (AWS) data center infrastructure in the United Arab Emirates and Bahrain experienced service disruptions following reported drone strikes in the region.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] AWS applies charges for data transferred both between Availability Zones within the same region (inter-AZ) and across different geographic regions (inter-region).
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] The pricing structure is influenced by several factors, including the source and destination of the data, the specific AWS services in use, and the underlying networking architecture.
[src:aws-quicksight/amazon-quicksight] Various services implement different data transfer models, and the choice of communication method—such as VPC Peering, Transit Gateway, or AWS PrivateLink—can also affect the overall cost.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] BI tools can handle large amounts of structured and sometimes unstructured data to help organizations identify, develop, and otherwise create new strategic business opportunities.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] They aim to allow for the easy interpretation of these big data.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Identifying new opportunities and implementing an effective strategy based on insights is assumed to potentially provide businesses with a competitive market advantage and long-term stability, and help them take strategic decisions.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Business intelligence can be used by enterprises to support a wide range of business decisions ranging from operational to strategic.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Basic operating decisions include product positioning or pricing.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Strategic business decisions involve priorities, goals, and directions at the broadest level.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] In all cases, business intelligence is considered most effective when it combines data from the market in which a company operates (external data) with data from internal company sources, such as financial and operational information.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] When integrated, external and internal data provide a comprehensive view that creates ‘intelligence’ not possible from any single data source alone.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Among their many uses, business intelligence tools empower organizations to gain insight into new markets, to assess demand and suitability of products and services for different market segments, and to gauge the impact of marketing efforts.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] BI applications use data gathered from a data warehouse (DW) or from a data mart, and the concepts of BI and DW combine as "BI/DW" or as "BIDW".
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] A data warehouse contains a copy of analytical data that facilitates decision support.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] The earliest known use of the term *business intelligence* is in Richard Millar Devens' *Cyclopædia of Commercial and Business Anecdotes* (1865).
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] The ability to collect and react accordingly based on the information retrieved, Devens says, is central to business intelligence.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] In 1989, Howard Dresner (later a Gartner analyst) proposed *business intelligence* as an umbrella term to describe "concepts and methods to improve business decision making by using fact-based support systems." It was not until the late 1990s that this usage was widespread.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Therefore, Forrester refers to *data preparation* and *data usage* as two separate but closely linked segments of the business-intelligence architectural stack.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] If understood broadly, competitive intelligence can be considered as a subset of business intelligence.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Business intelligence and business analytics are sometimes used interchangeably, but there are alternate definitions.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Thomas Davenport, professor of information technology and management at Babson College argues that business intelligence should be divided into querying, reporting, Online analytical processing (OLAP), an "alerts" tool, and business analytics.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] In this definition, business analytics is the subset of BI focusing on statistics, prediction, and optimization, rather than the reporting functionality.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Business operations can generate a very large amount of data in the form of emails, memos, notes from call centers, news, user groups, chats, reports, web pages, presentations, image files, video files, and marketing material.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] According to Merrill Lynch, more than 85% of all business information exists in these forms; a company might only use such a document a single time.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Because of the way it is produced and stored, this information is either unstructured or semi-structured.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] The management of semi-structured data is an unsolved problem in the information technology industry.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] According to projections from Gartner (2003), white-collar workers spend 30–40% of their time searching, finding, and assessing unstructured data.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] BI uses both structured and unstructured data.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] The former is easy to search, and the latter contains a large quantity of the information needed for analysis and decision-making.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Because of the difficulty of properly searching, finding, and assessing unstructured or semi-structured data, organizations may not draw upon these vast reservoirs of information, which could influence a particular decision, task, or project.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] This can ultimately lead to poorly informed decision-making.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Therefore, when designing a business intelligence/DW solution, the specific problems associated with semi-structured and unstructured data must be accommodated, as well as those associated with structured data.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] There are several challenges to developing BI with semi-structured data.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] To solve problems with searchability and assessment of data, it is necessary to know something about the content.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] This can be done by adding context through the use of metadata.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Many systems already capture some metadata (e.g. filename, author, size, etc.), but more useful would be metadata about the actual content – e.g. summaries, topics, people, or companies mentioned.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Two technologies designed for generating metadata about content are automatic categorization and information extraction.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Generative business intelligence is the application of generative AI techniques, such as large language models, in business intelligence.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] This combination facilitates data analysis and enables users to interact with data more intuitively, generating actionable insights through natural language queries.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Microsoft Copilot was, for example, integrated into the business analytics tool Power BI.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] In a 2013 report, Gartner categorized business intelligence vendors as either an independent "pure-play" vendor or a consolidated "mega-vendor".
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] In 2019, the BI market was shaken within Europe for the new legislation of GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) which puts the responsibility of data collection and storage onto the data user with strict laws in place to make sure the data is compliant.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Growth within Europe has steadily increased since May 2019 when GDPR was brought in.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] The legislation refocused companies to look at their own data from a compliance perspective but also revealed future opportunities using personalization and external BI providers to increase market share.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] A Business Intelligence Competency Center (BICC) is a team that supports the use of business intelligence in an organization.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Since 2001, the BICC concept has been refined through implementations in organizations that have adopted BI and related analytical software.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Usage of the term BICC has varied significantly across implementations in different organizations.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] The adoption of the BICC concept has led some organizations to establish units that focus on the use of BI software for decision-making, which may increase the value an organization derives from its BI implementation.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] A BICC coordinates activities and resources to facilitate a fact-based approach to decision-making within an organization.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] It has responsibility for the governance structure for BI and the use of analytical programs, projects, practices, software, and architecture.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] A BICC is responsible for developing plans, priorities, infrastructure, and competencies that can support strategic decision-making using BI and analytical software.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] In recent years, knowledge-oriented shared service centers have emerged in many organizations.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Their primary focus has been the offering of analytics and data mining as an internal service across the organization.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Such a center may be referred to as an Analytics Competency Center (ACC), Analytics Center of Excellence, Analytics Service Center, Big Data CoC, or Big Data Lab.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] By the end of 2017, a report by Gartner Research estimated that approximately 25% of large firms had a dedicated ACC unit (or equivalent) for data and analytics.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] In contrast to classic BICCs, these centers do not place emphasis on reporting, historical analysis, and dashboards.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] ACCs aim to enhance a company's data capabilities by building expertise in data analytics, formulating a data strategy, identifying use cases for data mining, and promoting the adoption of analytics within the organization.
[src:aws-quicksight/business-intelligence] Although BICCs can change into ACCs, new ACC formations can also occur in practice.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] In computer information systems, a **dashboard** is a type of graphical user interface which often provides at-a-glance views of data relevant to a particular objective or process through a combination of visualizations and summary information.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] In other usage, "dashboard" is another name for "progress report" or "report" and is considered a form of data visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The dashboard is often accessible by a web browser and is typically linked to regularly updating data sources.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are often interactive and facilitate users to explore the data themselves, usually by clicking into elements to view more detailed information.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The term dashboard originates from the automobile dashboard where drivers monitor the major functions at a glance via the instrument panel.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The idea of digital dashboards followed the study of decision support systems in the 1970s.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Early predecessors of the modern business dashboard were first developed in the 1980s in the form of Executive Information Systems (EISs).
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Due to problems primarily with data refreshing and handling, it was soon realized that the approach wasn't practical as information was often incomplete, unreliable, and spread across too many disparate sources.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Thus, EISs hibernated until the 1990s when the information age quickened pace and data warehousing, and online analytical processing (OLAP) allowed dashboards to function adequately.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Despite the availability of enabling technologies, the dashboard use didn't become popular until later in that decade, with the rise of key performance indicators (KPIs), and the introduction of Robert S.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] In the late 1990s, Microsoft promoted a concept known as the Digital Nervous System and "digital dashboards" were described as being one leg of that concept.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Today, the use of dashboards forms an important part of Business Performance Management (BPM).
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Initially dashboards were used for monitoring purposes, now with the advancement of technology, dashboards are being used for more analytical purposes.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The use of dashboards has now been incorporating; scenario analysis, drill down capabilities, and presentation format flexibility.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboards allow managers to monitor the contribution of the various departments in their organization.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] In addition, they enable “rolling up” of information to present a consolidated view across an organization.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] To gauge exactly how well an organization is performing overall, digital dashboards allow you to capture and report specific data points from each department within the organization, thus providing a "snapshot" of performance.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards offers a holistic view of the entire business as it gives the manager a bird's eye view into the performance of sales, data inventory, web traffic, social media analytics and other associated data that is visually presented on a single dashboard.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards lead to better management of marketing/financial strategies as a dashboard for the display of marketing data makes the process of marketing easier and more reliable as compared to doing it manually.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Web analytics play a crucial role in shaping the marketing strategy of many businesses.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards also facilitate for better tracking of sales and financial reporting as the data is more precise and in one area.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Lastly, dashboards offer for better customer service through monitoring because they keep both the managers and the clients updated on the project progress through automated emails and notifications.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards can be broken down according to role and are either strategic, analytical, operational, or informational.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are the 3rd step on the information ladder, demonstrating the conversion of data to increasingly valuable insights.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Strategic dashboards support managers at any level in an organization and provide the quick overview that decision-makers need to monitor the health and opportunities of the business.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards of this type focus on high-level measures of performance and forecasts.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Strategic dashboards benefit from static snapshots of data (daily, weekly, monthly, and quarterly) that are not constantly changing from one moment to the next.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards for analytical purposes often include more context, comparisons, and history, along with subtler performance evaluators.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] In addition, analytical dashboards typically support interactions with the data, such as drilling down into the underlying details.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards for monitoring operations are often designed differently from those that support strategic decision making or data analysis and often require monitoring of activities and events that are constantly changing and might require attention and response at a moment's notice.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboards may be laid out to track the flows inherent in the business processes that they monitor.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Graphically, users may see the high-level processes and then drill down into low-level data.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] This level of detail is often buried deep within the corporate enterprise and otherwise unavailable to the senior executives.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Three main types of digital dashboards dominate the market today: desktop software applications, web-browser-based applications, and desktop applications are also known as desktop widgets.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Both Desktop and Browser-based providers enable the distribution of dashboards via a web browser.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] An example of the latter is web-based-browser Asana, which helps teams orchestrate their work, from daily tasks to strategic cross-functional initiatives.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] With it, teams can manage everything from company objectives to digital transformation to product launches and marketing campaigns.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Specialized dashboards may track all corporate functions.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Examples include human resources, recruiting, sales, operations, security, information technology, project management, customer relationship management, digital marketing and many more departmental dashboards.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] For a smaller organization like a startup a compact startup scorecard dashboard tracks important activities across lot of domains ranging from social media to sales.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboard projects involve business units as the driver and the information technology department as the enabler.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Therefore, the success of dashboard projects depends on the relevancy/importance of information provided within the dashboard.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] This includes the metrics chosen to monitor and the timeliness of the data forming those metrics; data must be up to date and accurate.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Key performance indicators, balanced scorecards, and sales performance figures are some of the content appropriate on business dashboards.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards involve the combination of visual and functional features.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] This combination of features helps improve cognition and interpretation.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] A performance dashboard sits at the intersection of two powerful disciplines: business intelligence and performance management.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Therefore, there are different users who could use these dashboards for different reasons.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] For example, a level of workers could look at monitoring inventory while those in more managerial roles can look at lagging measure.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Then executives could utilize the dashboard to evaluate strategic performance against objectives.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Balanced scorecards and dashboards have been linked together as if they were interchangeable.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] However, although both visually display critical information, the difference is in the format: Scorecards can open the quality of an operation while dashboards provide calculated direction.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] A balanced scorecard has what they called a "prescriptive" format.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Each of these sections ensures that a Balanced Scorecard is essentially connected to the businesses critical strategic needs.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The design of a dashboard is more loosely defined.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are usually a series of graphics, charts, gauges and other visual indicators that can be monitored and interpreted.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Even when there is a strategic link, on a dashboard, it may not be noticed as such since objectives are not normally present on dashboards.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] However, dashboards can be customized to link their graphs and charts to strategic objectives.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Digital dashboard technology is available "out-of-the-box" from many software providers.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Some companies, however, continue to do in-house development and maintenance of dashboard applications.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] For example, GE Aviation has developed a proprietary software/portal called "Digital Cockpit" to monitor the trends in the aircraft spare parts business.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] A good information design will clearly communicate key information to users and makes supporting information easily accessible.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] There are a few key elements to a good dashboard:.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] A research-based framework for Business Intelligence dashboard design suggests that "cross-visual interactivity" is the most impactful of all features.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards serve as a visual representation for a company to monitor progress and trends, not only among themselves but against other companies as well.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards and visualizations contain data that is updated in real time.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] For example, if the underlying data in an Excel spreadsheet were to change, so would the visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Power BI provides the tools for a user to create different types of visualizations to communicate the data that they are using.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Some examples of these visualizations include graphs, maps, and clustered columns.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Power BI pulls data from Excel that can be used to create dashboards and visualizations.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Whereas Excel does not import data from Power BI.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Excel is typically used for less data and Power BI is more complex.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Power BI can be used to display trends over time.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] For example, a company can create a time plot that shows its costs and revenues over a certain period.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The data can then be arranged to show per day, month, quarter, year, etc.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] This requires simple formatting tools so the data can quickly be changed and compared.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Power BI allows the user to customize their visualizations by adding colors and labels.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] In addition, when the user clicks a data point, they are able to understand what the point or selection is showing.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Power BI also has a commonly used map feature where businesses can view their sales and earnings across different states and countries.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Places with the highest amounts of data will appear larger in size.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] For example, a state with the most revenue will be bigger than states with less data.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Power BI is also interactive in that in any type of map a person can expand a specific category to look deeper into the data contained.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Tableau is another program that allows users to create dashboards.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Allegedly, One of Tableau's biggest advantages is how much data it can hold.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Tableau can hold an unlimited amount, whereas an Excel spreadsheet has a capacity of 1,048,576 rows.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] However, it is possible to hold and analyze effectively billions of rows in Excel, using its Power Pivot feature.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Tableau has the ability to make interactive dashboards by clicking into a specific point.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] For example, you can have data be displayed within a map.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] By clicking a specific state or city you can get a closer look at the data contained within that location.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Filters and parameters can also be added.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] For example, if one were to analyze revenues across the United States you could set a parameter to only show salaries within a particular range.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Once set, only states within this range will be highlighted.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Excel has many tools that help the user not only implement data but also visualize data.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Excel has many built in functions that can help break down data and also separate data by scenarios.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The user can easily download and add files to their Excel sheets to use for their data.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Other tools Excel offers is the use of conditional formatting and basic pivot tables and charts.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Excel allows the user to reference other cells which ultimately allows for complex computations to be made and conclusions to be drawn from data.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] There are certain guidelines that can be useful when creating dashboards and other visualizations.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The guidelines have a structure that can be followed and that is beginning with reading direction.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] When it comes to how you are arranging your information on your dashboard or a visualization it can be helpful to think about reading direction.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] General reading direction is from left to right and from top to bottom.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Having information flow in this structure will allow others to read and understand your visuals in a more natural structure.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Local proximity is another idea to keep in mind when creating a visual or a dashboard.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Having information in a close proximity can be compared with a better effectiveness and allow users to draw conclusions.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Being able to make sure the user is not being overloaded with information when creating your visual.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Having a few key figures with significant importance can be more helpful compared to having too much information.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] When you have too much information and not a structure to what you are presenting then that is known as a “data graveyard”.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Another aspect to keep in mind while creating visuals that goes along with information overload is the idea of interaction within your visual.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Interacting with the dashboard would allow for further detail to be obtained from the user and allow them to better understand the information on your dashboard.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Chart visualization is an important aspect when creating dashboards, diagrams in particular.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] When you have complex data it can be difficult to come to conclusions from that material and being able to have different visual elements within the dashboard can be helpful in giving a larger overview of the material.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Being able to have a visual reporting system allows multiple processing operations to be carried out and that could increase the effectiveness of decisions.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] There are different types of visualizations that can be seen as more effective depending on the data type and the recipient.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Looking at traditional business graphics in an interactive form is another aspect to keep in mind when creating a dashboard.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Business charts are used mainly in the form of interactive dashboards.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] A major advantage of business charts is that the majority of users have an understanding of them.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] There are many connections between dashboards and accounting.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards aid with budgeting, management control, and wage control.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are used to present data in a quick and easy to read way.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The ability to present data in a quick way with a visual allows for more data to be processed and understood.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are used for performance reports, sales analysis on sectors, and inventory rotation.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards should be quick visualizations that allow decisions to be made quicker than they usually would without the access to dashboard technology.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] Dashboards are also used in accounting decision making settings.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] The data can help prove a change is efficient or inefficient and therefore help with improving systems throughout an organization.
[src:aws-quicksight/dashboard-computing] In order for a dashboard to be efficient, the individual creating the dashboard needs to make sure that the information is simple and easy to read and be interpreted.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] In addition, **Narrative visualization** is a method that uses visual elements such as charts, graphs, maps and the like to convey data or information.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] This approach blends data analysis, storytelling, and visualization to present information through structured narrative flows- *using visuals not just to present statistics, but to tell a story through data*.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Its goal is to help people identify trends, patterns, and relationships in data through a compelling story-driven visual experience.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Emerging technologies like virtual, augmented and mixed reality have the potential to make information visualization more immersive, intuitive, interactive and easily manipulable and thus enhance the user's visual perception and cognition.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Effective data visualization is well-sourced, appropriately contextualized, and presented in a simple, uncluttered manner.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The underlying data is accurate and up-to-date to ensure insights are reliable.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Graphical items are well-chosen and aesthetically appealing, with shapes, colors and other visual elements used deliberately in a meaningful and non-distracting manner.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The visuals are accompanied by supporting texts.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Verbal and graphical components complement each other to ensure clear, quick and memorable understanding.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Effective information visualization is aware of the needs and expertise level of the target audience.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data scientists, analysts and data mining specialists use data visualization to check data quality, find errors, unusual gaps, missing values, clean data, explore the structures and features of data, and assess outputs of data-driven models.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization can be part of *data storytelling*, where they are paired with a narrative structure, to contextualize the analyzed data and communicate insights gained from analyzing it to convince the audience into making a decision or taking action.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization is interdisciplinary, it incorporates principles found in descriptive statistics, visual communication, graphic design, cognitive science and, interactive computer graphics and human-computer interaction.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Since effective visualization requires design skills, statistical skills and computing skills, it is both an art and a science.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Visual analytics combines statistical data analysis, data and information visualization, and human analytical reasoning through interactive visual interfaces to help users reach conclusions, gain actionable insights and make informed decisions which are otherwise difficult for computers to do.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Research into how people read and misread types of visualizations helps to determine what types and features of visualizations are most understandable and effective.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Unintentionally poor or intentionally misleading and deceptive visualizations can function as powerful tools which disseminate misinformation, manipulate public perception and divert public opinion.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Thus data visualization literacy has become an important component of data and information literacy in the information age akin to the roles played by textual, mathematical and visual literacy in the past.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The field of data and information visualization has emerged "from research in human–computer interaction, computer science, graphics, visual design, psychology, photography and business methods.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] It is increasingly applied as a critical component in scientific research, digital libraries, data mining, financial data analysis, market studies, manufacturing production control, and drug discovery".
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data and information visualization presumes that "visual representations and interaction techniques take advantage of the human eye's broad bandwidth pathway into the mind to allow users to see, explore, and understand large amounts of information at once.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data analysis is an indispensable part of all applied research and problem solving in industry.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Among these approaches, information visualization, or visual data analysis, is the most reliant on the cognitive skills of human analysts, and allows the discovery of unstructured actionable insights that are limited only by human imagination and creativity.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The analyst does not have to learn any sophisticated methods to be able to interpret the visualizations of the data.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Information visualization is also a hypothesis generation scheme, which can be, and is typically followed by more analytical or formal analysis, such as statistical hypothesis testing.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] To communicate information clearly and efficiently, data visualization uses statistical graphics, plots, information graphics and other tools.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Numerical data may be encoded using dots, lines, or bars, to visually communicate a quantitative message.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Effective visualization helps users analyze and reason about data and evidence.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] It makes complex data more accessible, understandable, and usable, but can also be reductive.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Users may have particular analytical tasks, such as making comparisons or understanding causality, and the design principle of the graphic (i.e., showing comparisons or showing causality) follows the task.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Tables are generally used where users will look up a specific measurement, while charts of various types are used to show patterns or relationships in the data for one or more variables.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization refers to the techniques used to communicate data or information by encoding it as visual objects (e.g., points, lines, or bars) contained in graphics.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The goal is to communicate information clearly and efficiently to users.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] It is one of the steps in data analysis or data science.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] According to Vitaly Friedman (2008) the "main goal of data visualization is to communicate information clearly and effectively through graphical means.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] It doesn't mean that data visualization needs to look boring to be functional or extremely sophisticated to look beautiful.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] To convey ideas effectively, both aesthetic form and functionality need to go hand in hand, providing insights into a rather sparse and complex data set by communicating its key aspects in a more intuitive way.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Yet designers often fail to achieve a balance between form and function, creating gorgeous data visualizations which fail to serve their main purpose — to communicate information".
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Wattenberg suggested that an ideal visualization should not only communicate clearly, but stimulate viewer engagement and attention.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is closely related to information graphics, information visualization, scientific visualization, exploratory data analysis and statistical graphics.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] In the new millennium, data visualization has become an active area of research, teaching and development.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] (2002), it has united scientific and information visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] In the commercial environment data visualization is often referred to as dashboards.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Infographics are another very common form of data visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Edward Tufte has explained that users of information displays are executing particular *analytical tasks* such as making comparisons.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The *design principle* of the information graphic should support the analytical task.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] As William Cleveland and Robert McGill show, different graphical elements accomplish this more or less effectively.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] For example, dot plots and bar charts outperform pie charts.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] In his 1983 book *The Visual Display of Quantitative Information*, Edward Tufte defines 'graphical displays' and principles for effective graphical display in the following passage: "Excellence in statistical graphics consists of complex ideas communicated with clarity, precision, and efficiency.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] For example, the Minard diagram shows the losses suffered by Napoleon's army in the 1812–1813 period.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Six variables are plotted: the size of the army, its location on a two-dimensional surface (x and y), time, the direction of movement, and temperature.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The line width illustrates a comparison (size of the army at points in time), while the temperature axis suggests a cause of the change in army size.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] This multivariate display on a two-dimensional surface tells a story that can be grasped immediately while identifying the source data to build credibility.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Not applying these principles may result in misleading graphs, distorting the message, or supporting an erroneous conclusion.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] According to Tufte, chartjunk refers to the extraneous interior decoration of the graphic that does not enhance the message or gratuitous three-dimensional or perspective effects.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Needlessly separating the explanatory key from the image itself, requiring the eye to travel back and forth from the image to the key, is a form of "administrative debris." The ratio of "data to ink" should be maximized, erasing non-data ink where feasible.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The Congressional Budget Office summarized several best practices for graphical displays in a June 2014 presentation.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] These included: a) Knowing your audience; b) Designing graphics that can stand alone outside the report's context; and c) Designing graphics that communicate the key messages in the report.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] For greatest efficiency and simplicity of design and user experience, this readability is enhanced through the use of bijective mapping in that design of the image elements - where the mapping of representational element to data variable is unique.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Kosara (2007) also identifies the need for a visualisation to be "recognisable as a visualisation and not appear to be something else".
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] He also states that recognisability and readability may not always be required in all types of visualisation e.g.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] "informative art" (which would still meet all three above criteria but might not look like a visualisation) or "artistic visualisation" (which similarly is still based on non-visual data to create an image, but may not be readable or recognisable).
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Ranking: Categorical subdivisions are ranked in ascending or descending order, such as a ranking of sales performance (the *measure*) by sales persons (the *category*, with each sales person a *categorical subdivision*) during a single period.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used to show the comparison across the sales persons.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Part-to-whole: Categorical subdivisions are measured as a ratio to the whole (i.e., a percentage out of 100%).
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] A pie chart or bar chart can show the comparison of ratios, such as the market share represented by competitors in a market.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Deviation: Categorical subdivisions are compared against a reference, such as a comparison of actual vs. budget expenses for several departments of a business for a given time period.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart can show comparison of the actual versus the reference amount.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Frequency distribution: Shows the number of observations of a particular variable for given interval, such as the number of years in which the stock market return is between intervals such as 0–10%, 11–20%, etc.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] A histogram, a type of bar chart, may be used for this analysis.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] A boxplot helps visualize key statistics about the distribution, such as median, quartiles, outliers, etc.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Correlation: Comparison between observations represented by two variables (X,Y) to determine if they tend to move in the same or opposite directions.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] For example, plotting unemployment (X) and inflation (Y) for a sample of months.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] A scatter plot is typically used for this message.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Nominal comparison: Comparing categorical subdivisions in no particular order, such as the sales volume by product code.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] A bar chart may be used for this comparison.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Geographic or geospatial: Comparison of a variable across a map or layout, such as the unemployment rate by state or the number of persons on the various floors of a building.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Analysts reviewing a set of data may consider whether some or all of the messages and graphic types above are applicable to their task and audience.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The process of trial and error to identify meaningful relationships and messages in the data is part of exploratory data analysis.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] A human can distinguish differences in line length, shape, orientation, distances, and color (hue) readily without significant processing effort; these are referred to as "pre-attentive attributes".
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] For example, it may require significant time and effort ("attentive processing") to identify the number of times the digit "5" appears in a series of numbers; but if that digit is different in size, orientation, or color, instances of the digit can be noted quickly through pre-attentive processing.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Compelling graphics take advantage of pre-attentive processing and attributes and the relative strength of these attributes.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] For example, since humans can more easily process differences in line length than surface area, it may be more effective to use a bar chart (which takes advantage of line length to show comparison) rather than pie charts (which use surface area to show comparison).
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Almost all data visualizations are created for human consumption.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Knowledge of human perception and cognition is necessary when designing intuitive visualizations.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Cognition refers to processes in human beings like perception, attention, learning, memory, thought, concept formation, reading, and problem solving.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Human visual processing is efficient in detecting changes and making comparisons between quantities, sizes, shapes and variations in lightness.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] When properties of symbolic data are mapped to visual properties, humans can browse through large amounts of data efficiently.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] It is estimated that 2/3 of the brain's neurons can be involved in visual processing.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Proper visualization provides a different approach to show potential connections, relationships, etc. which are not as obvious in non-visualized quantitative data.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Visualization can become a means of data exploration.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Studies have shown individuals used on average 19% less cognitive resources, and 4.5% better able to recall details when comparing data visualization with text.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] There is no comprehensive history of data visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] There are no accounts that span the entire development of visual thinking and visual representation of data, and which collate the contributions of disparate disciplines.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Michael Friendly and Daniel Denis of York University are engaged in a project that attempts to provide a comprehensive history of visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization is not a modern development.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Since prehistory, stellar data, or information such as location of stars were visualized on the walls of caves (such as those found in Lascaux Cave in Southern France) since the Pleistocene era.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Physical artefacts such as Mesopotamian clay tokens (5500 BC), Inca quipus (2600 BC) and Marshall Islands stick charts (n.d.) can also be considered as visualizing quantitative information.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The first documented data visualization can be tracked back to 1160 B.C. with the Turin Papyrus Map which accurately illustrates the distribution of geological resources and provides information about quarrying of those resources.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Such maps can be categorized as thematic cartography, which is a type of data visualization that presents and communicates specific data and information through a geographical illustration designed to show a particular theme connected with a specific geographic area.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Earliest documented forms of data visualization were various thematic maps from different cultures and ideograms and hieroglyphs that provided and allowed interpretation of information illustrated.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] For example, Linear B tablets of Mycenae provided a visualization of information regarding Late Bronze Age era trades in the Mediterranean.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The idea of coordinates was used by ancient Egyptian surveyors in laying out towns, earthly and heavenly positions were located by something akin to latitude and longitude at least by 200 BC, and the map projection of a spherical Earth into latitude and longitude by Claudius Ptolemy [c.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] 165] in Alexandria would serve as reference standards until the 14th century.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The invention of paper and parchment allowed further development of visualizations.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] One graph from the 10th or possibly 11th century is an illustration of planetary movements, used in an appendix of a textbook in monastery schools.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The graph apparently was meant to represent a plot of the inclinations of the planetary orbits as a function of the time.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] For this purpose, the zone of the zodiac was represented on a plane with a horizontal line divided into thirty parts as the time or longitudinal axis.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The vertical axis designates the width of the zodiac.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The horizontal scale appears to have been chosen for each planet individually for the periods cannot be reconciled.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The accompanying text refers only to the amplitudes.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The curves are apparently not related in time.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] By the 16th century, techniques and instruments for precise observation and measurement of physical quantities, and geographic and celestial position were well-developed (for example, a "wall quadrant" constructed by Tycho Brahe [1546–1601], covering an entire wall in his observatory).
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Particularly important were the development of triangulation and other methods to determine mapping locations accurately.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Very early, the measure of time led scholars to develop innovative way of visualizing the data (e.g.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Lorenz Codomann in 1596, Johannes Temporarius in 1596).
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Mathematicians René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat developed analytic geometry and two-dimensional coordinate system which heavily influenced the practical methods of displaying and calculating values.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Fermat and Blaise Pascal's work on statistics and probability theory laid the groundwork for what we now conceptualize as data.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] These developments helped William Playfair, who saw potential for graphical communication of quantitative data, to generate and develop graphical methods of statistics.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] In 1786, Playfair published the first presentation graphics.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, Jacques Bertin used quantitative graphs to represent information "intuitively, clearly, accurately, and efficiently".
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] John Tukey and Edward Tufte pushed the bounds of data visualization; Tukey with his new statistical approach of exploratory data analysis and Tufte with his book "The Visual Display of Quantitative Information" paved the way for refining data visualization techniques for more than statisticians.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] With the progression of technology came the progression of data visualization; starting with hand-drawn visualizations and evolving into more technical applications – including interactive designs leading to software visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The modern study of visualization started with computer graphics, which "has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] However, in its early days the lack of graphics power often limited its usefulness.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the special issue of Computer Graphics on Visualization in *Scientific Computing*.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Since then there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH".
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] They have been devoted to the general topics of data visualization, information visualization and scientific visualization, and more specific areas such as volume visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Programs like SAS, SOFA, R, Minitab, Cornerstone and more allow for data visualization in the field of statistics.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Other data visualization applications, more focused and unique to individuals, programming languages such as D3, Python (through matplotlib, seaborn) and JavaScript and Java(through JavaFX) help to make the visualization of quantitative data a possibility.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Private schools have also developed programs to meet the demand for learning data visualization and associated programming libraries, including free programs like The Data Incubator or paid programs like General Assembly.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Beginning with the symposium "Data to Discovery" in 2013, ArtCenter College of Design, Caltech and JPL in Pasadena have run an annual program on interactive data visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The program asks: How can interactive data visualization help scientists and engineers explore their data more effectively?
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] How can computing, design, and design thinking help maximize research results?
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] What methodologies are most effective for leveraging knowledge from these fields?
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] In recent years, with the increasing popularity of games, data and information visualization has been gradually applied in the gaming industry through the use of analytical tools to assess player statistics and game performance, which are visualized in the form of health points, maps, and diagrams.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The data is then collected and stored by developers.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The implementation of these tools in gaming assists developers in improving user experience and in the development and updating of newer games.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Data visualization involves specific terminology, some of which is derived from statistics.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The distinction between quantitative and categorical variables is important because the two types require different methods of visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Two primary types of information displays are tables and graphs.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Eppler and Lengler have developed the "Periodic Table of Visualization Methods," an interactive chart displaying various data visualization methods.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] It includes six types of data visualization methods: data, information, concept, strategy, metaphor and compound.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Interactive data visualization has been a pursuit of statisticians since the late 1960s.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Examples of the developments can be found on the American Statistical Association video lending library.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] There are different approaches on the scope of data visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] One common focus is on information presentation, such as Friedman (2008).
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Friendly (2008) presumes two main parts of data visualization: statistical graphics, and thematic cartography.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] All these subjects are closely related to graphic design and information representation.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Within The Harvard Business Review, Scott Berinato developed a framework to approach data visualisation.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] To start thinking visually, users must consider two questions; 1) What you have and 2) what you're doing.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] The first step is identifying what data you want visualised.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] It is data-driven like profit over the past ten years or a conceptual idea like how a specific organisation is structured.
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Once this question is answered one can then focus on whether they are trying to communicate information (declarative visualisation) or trying to figure something out (exploratory visualisation).
[src:aws-quicksight/data-visualization-p01] Scott Berinato combines these questions to give four types of visual communication that each have their own goals.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Visualization today has ever-expanding applications in science, education, engineering (e.g., product visualization), interactive multimedia, medicine, etc.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Typical of a visualization application is the field of computer graphics.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The invention of computer graphics (and 3D computer graphics) may be the most important development in visualization since the invention of central perspective in the Renaissance period.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The development of animation also helped advance visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The use of visualization to present information is not a new phenomenon.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] It has been used in maps, scientific drawings, and data plots for over a thousand years.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Examples from cartography include Ptolemy's Geographia (2nd century AD), a map of China (1137 AD), and Minard's map (1861) of Napoleon's invasion of Russia a century and a half ago.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Most of the concepts learned in devising these images carry over in a straightforward manner to computer visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Edward Tufte has written three critically acclaimed books that explain many of these principles.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Computer graphics has from its beginning been used to study scientific problems.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The recent emphasis on visualization started in 1987 with the publication of Visualization in Scientific Computing, a special issue of Computer Graphics.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Since then, there have been several conferences and workshops, co-sponsored by the IEEE Computer Society and ACM SIGGRAPH, devoted to the general topic, and special areas in the field, for example volume visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Most people are familiar with the digital animations produced to present meteorological data during weather reports on television, though few can distinguish between those models of reality and the satellite photos that are also shown on such programs.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] TV also offers scientific visualizations when it shows computer drawn and animated reconstructions of road or airplane accidents.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Some of the most popular examples of scientific visualizations are computer-generated images that show real spacecraft in action, out in the void far beyond Earth, or on other planets.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Dynamic forms of visualization, such as educational animation or timelines, have the potential to enhance learning about systems that change over time.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Apart from the distinction between interactive visualizations and animation, the most useful categorization is probably between abstract and model-based scientific visualizations.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The abstract visualizations show completely conceptual constructs in 2D or 3D.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] These generated shapes are completely arbitrary.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The model-based visualizations either place overlays of data on real or digitally constructed images of reality or make a digital construction of a real object directly from the scientific data.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is usually done with specialized software, though there are a few exceptions, noted below.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Some of these specialized programs have been released as open source software, having very often its origins in universities, within an academic environment where sharing software tools and giving access to the source code is common.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] There are also many proprietary software packages of scientific visualization tools.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Models and frameworks for building visualizations include the data flow models popularized by systems such as AVS, IRIS Explorer, and VTK toolkit, and data state models in spreadsheet systems such as the Spreadsheet for Visualization and Spreadsheet for Images.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] As a subject in computer science, scientific visualization is the use of interactive, sensory representations, typically visual, of abstract data to reinforce cognition, hypothesis building, and reasoning.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization is the transformation, selection, or representation of data from simulations or experiments, with an implicit or explicit geometric structure, to allow the exploration, analysis, and understanding of the data.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Scientific visualization focuses and emphasizes the representation of higher order data using primarily graphics and animation techniques.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] It is a very important part of visualization and maybe the first one, as the visualization of experiments and phenomena is as old as science itself.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Traditional areas of scientific visualization are flow visualization, medical visualization, astrophysical visualization, and chemical visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] There are several different techniques to visualize scientific data, with isosurface reconstruction and direct volume rendering being the more common.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Data visualization is a related subcategory of visualization dealing with statistical graphics and geospatial data (as in thematic cartography) that is abstracted in schematic form.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to explore large amount of abstract data.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The term "information visualization" was originally coined by the User Interface Research Group at Xerox PARC and included Jock Mackinlay.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Practical application of information visualization in computer programs involves selecting, transforming, and representing abstract data in a form that facilitates human interaction for exploration and understanding.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Important aspects of information visualization are dynamics of visual representation and the interactivity.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Strong techniques enable the user to modify the visualization in real-time, thus affording unparalleled perception of patterns and structural relations in the abstract data in question.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Educational visualization is using a simulation to create an image of something so it can be taught about.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] This is very useful when teaching about a topic that is difficult to otherwise see, for example, atomic structure, because atoms are far too small to be studied easily without expensive and difficult to use scientific equipment.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The use of visual representations to transfer knowledge between at least two persons aims to improve the transfer of knowledge by using computer and non-computer-based visualization methods complementarily.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Thus properly designed visualization is an important part of not only data analysis but knowledge transfer process, too.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Knowledge transfer may be significantly improved using hybrid designs as it enhances information density but may decrease clarity as well.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] For example, visualization of a 3D scalar field may be implemented using iso-surfaces for field distribution and textures for the gradient of the field.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Examples of such visual formats are sketches, diagrams, images, objects, interactive visualizations, information visualization applications, and imaginary visualizations as in stories.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] While information visualization concentrates on the use of computer-supported tools to derive new insights, knowledge visualization focuses on transferring insights and creating new knowledge in groups.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Beyond the mere transfer of facts, knowledge visualization aims to further transfer insights, experiences, attitudes, values, expectations, perspectives, opinions, and estimates in different fields by using various complementary visualizations.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Product visualization involves visualization software technology for the viewing and manipulation of 3D models, technical drawing and other related documentation of manufactured components and large assemblies of products.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] It is a key part of product lifecycle management.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Product visualization software typically provides high levels of photorealism so that a product can be viewed before it is actually manufactured.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] This supports functions ranging from design and styling to sales and marketing.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] *Technical visualization* is an important aspect of product development.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Originally technical drawings were made by hand, but with the rise of advanced computer graphics the drawing board has been replaced by computer-aided design (CAD).
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] CAD-drawings and models have several advantages over hand-made drawings such as the possibility of 3-D modeling, rapid prototyping, and simulation.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] 3D product visualization promises more interactive experiences for online shoppers, but also challenges retailers to overcome hurdles in the production of 3D content, as large-scale 3D content production can be extremely costly and time-consuming.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] In recent years, product visualization has increasingly incorporated interactive and real-time technologies, particularly in e-commerce environments.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Modern 3D visualization tools enable users to explore products in detail, customize attributes such as color, materials, and configuration, and view items in simulated or real-world contexts.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] These capabilities enhance user engagement and support more informed decision-making by providing realistic and context-aware representations of products.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] As a result, product visualization can help reduce uncertainty prior to purchase and contribute to lower product return rates.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Visual communication is the communication of ideas through the visual display of information.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Primarily associated with two dimensional images, it includes: alphanumerics, art, signs, and electronic resources.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Recent research in the field has focused on web design and graphically oriented usability.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics focuses on human interaction with visualization systems as part of a larger process of data analysis.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics has been defined as "the science of analytical reasoning supported by the interactive visual interface".
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Its focus is on human information discourse (interaction) within massive, dynamically changing information spaces.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Visual analytics research concentrates on support for perceptual and cognitive operations that enable users to detect the expected and discover the unexpected in complex information spaces.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Technologies resulting from visual analytics find their application in almost all fields, but are being driven by critical needs (and funding) in biology and national security.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] One particular type of interactive visualization is virtual reality (VR), where the visual representation of information is presented using an immersive display device such as a stereo projector (see stereoscopy).
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Another type of interactive visualization is collaborative visualization, in which multiple people interact with the same computer visualization to communicate their ideas to each other or to explore information cooperatively.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Frequently, collaborative visualization is used when people are physically separated.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Using several networked computers, the same visualization can be presented to each person simultaneously.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The people then make annotations to the visualization as well as communicate via audio (i.e., telephone), video (i.e., a video-conference), or text (i.e., IRC) messages.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The Programmer's Hierarchical Interactive Graphics System (PHIGS) was one of the first programmatic efforts at interactive visualization and provided an enumeration of the types of input humans provide.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] All of these actions require a physical device.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Input devices range from the common – keyboards, mice, graphics tablets, trackballs, and touchpads – to the esoteric – wired gloves, boom arms, and even omnidirectional treadmills.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] These input actions can be used to control both the unique information being represented or the way that the information is presented.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] When the information being presented is altered, the visualization is usually part of a feedback loop.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] For example, consider an aircraft avionics system where the pilot inputs roll, pitch, and yaw and the visualization system provides a rendering of the aircraft's new attitude.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Another example would be a scientist who changes a simulation while it is running in response to a visualization of its current progress.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] This is called *computational steering*.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] More frequently, the representation of the information is changed rather than the information itself.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Experiments have shown that a delay of more than 20 ms between when input is provided and a visual representation is updated is noticeable by most people .
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Thus it is desirable for an interactive visualization to provide a rendering based on human input within this time frame.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] However, when large amounts of data must be processed to create a visualization, this becomes hard or even impossible with current technology.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Thus the term "interactive visualization" is usually applied to systems that provide feedback to users within several seconds of input.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The term *interactive framerate* is often used to measure how interactive a visualization is.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Framerates measure the frequency with which an image (a frame) can be generated by a visualization system.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] A framerate of 50 frames per second (frame/s) is considered good while 0.1 frame/s would be considered poor.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The use of framerates to characterize interactivity is slightly misleading however, since framerate is a measure of bandwidth while humans are more sensitive to latency.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Specifically, it is possible to achieve a good framerate of 50 frame/s but if the images generated refer to changes to the visualization that a person made more than 1 second ago, it will not feel interactive to a person.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] The rapid response time required for interactive visualization is a difficult constraint to meet and there are several approaches that have been explored to provide people with rapid visual feedback based on their input.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] *Progressive rendering* – where a framerate is guaranteed by rendering some subset of the information to be presented and providing incremental (progressive) improvements to the rendering once the visualization is no longer changing.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] *Level-of-detail (LOD) rendering* – where simplified representations of information are rendered to achieve a desired framerate while a person is providing input and then the full representation is used to generate a still image once the person is through manipulating the visualization.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] Subsampling can also be used to accelerate rendering techniques such as volume visualization that require more than twice the computations for an image twice the size.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] By rendering a smaller image and then scaling the image to fill the requested screen space, much less time is required to render the same data.
[src:aws-quicksight/interactive-visualization] *Frameless rendering* – where the visualization is no longer presented as a time series of images, but as a single image where different regions are updated over time.
